; // Ignore the newline after the total ratings for (int i = 0; i < totalRatings; i++) { std::string movieName; std::getline(file, movieName); int rating; file >> rating; file.ignore(); // Ignore the newline after the rating if (movieRatings.find(movieName) == movieRatings.end()) { movieRatings[movieName] = {rating, 1}; } else { movieRatings[movieName].first += rating; movieRatings[movieName].second++; } } file.close(); // Calculate and display average ratings for (const auto& pair : movieRatings) { const std::string& movieName = pair.first; double averageRating = pair.second.first / static_cast<double>(pair.second.second); std::cout << movieName << \\": \\" << pair.second.second << \\" review(s), average of \\" << averageRating << \\" / 5\\" << std::endl; } } int main() { std::string filename = \\"ratings.txt\\"; // Update with the actual filename analyzeRatings(filename); return 0; } \`\`\` In this implementation, we use a \`std::unordered_map\` called \`movieRatings\` to store each movie's total rating sum and review count in pairs. If a movie is encountered for the first time, a new pair is inserted into the map, otherwise, the existing pair is updated with the new rating. After reading the ratings from the file and populating the \`movieRatings\` map, we iterate over the map to calculate and display the average ratings for each movie. As before, remember to update the filename in the \`main\` function with the actual name of the file containing the ratings."},{"prompt":"What is the purpose of this following program Due date: 11-06-2023 (M), 9am Close date: 11-20-2023 (M), 9awhm Submission: a C++ file (hw6.cpp) on Blackboard Points: 40 Description: Movie Ratings Analysis You have collected a file of movie ratings where each movie is rated from 1 (bad) to 5 (excellent). The first line of the file is a number that identifies how many ratings are in the file. Each rating then consists of two lines: the name of the movie followed by the numeric rating from 1 to 5. Y